The structural discrepancies of a number of cembranoids (
Table 2
, 
Fig. 2
) isolated from 

Boswellia
species

have been observed. In some cases, this is due to the settlement of the structures based on the previous structures of the related compounds which were presented later in modified structural versions. For an example, a correlation was shown between the structure of cembrenol (
5
) and the earlier reported structure of incensole (
6A
) (
Fig. 5
). (
Klein and Obermann, 1978
). More recently, Hasegawa et al. mentioned that diterpenoids such as incensole (
6
) may be important odor components (
Hasegawa et al., 2012
).

The structures of some boscartin-type cembranoids (such as boscartin-M (
42
) and related compounds) have been correlated with those of incensole (
6
) and incensole acetate (
7
). The last two compounds have been suggested to act as the biogenetic precursors of these boscartins (discussed in Biogenesis). However, the wrong structures of incensole (
6
) and incensole acetate (
7
) have resulted from the wrong configuration of 5-β- OH (
Fig. 6
) (J. Wang et al., 2019).

It is interesting to mention that several cembranoids (such as boscartins AL-AO (
67–70
, 
67A–70A
) were also reported with the same names but with different structures (
Table 2
, 
Fig. 2
) (
Sun et al., 2019
; 
Wang et al., 2020
).

Incensole (
6
) and incensole acetate (
7
) have been considered as the biogenetic precursors of various boscartin-type cembranoids (Schemes 4 and 5) (
Sun et al., 2019
; J. Wang et al., 2019). These compounds underwent oxidation, isomerization and esterification to produce new boscartins derivatives. However, some biogenetic pathways have been reported with wrongly presented stereostructure of these compounds (Scheme 3) (
Sun et al., 2019
).

In the above scheme C-5 of incensole acetate (
7
) was presented with β- OAc but this compound contains α- OAc at C-5. Consequently, there should be a revision of the structure of boscartin M (
42
) and related compounds.

arthritis, bronchial asthma and several other related diseases. Incensole (
6
) and its derivatives have proven to contribute significantly to the overall activity of frankincense (Ahmed Al-Harrasi, Hidayat Hussain, Rene Csuk, 2018; 
Al-Harrasi et al., 2019a
).

Among several derivatives of incensole, the monoacetate and phenyl acetate esters showed a potent inhibitory activity on NF-κB activation but was not seen for serratol (
14
) (
Pollastro et al., 2016
).

In the brain of post-CHI (closed head injury) mice, incensole acetate (
7
) reduced glial activation and inhibited the expression of interleukin- 
IB
and TNFα m-RNAs, including cell death in macrophages at traumatized region. Incensole (
6
) (but not incensole acetate (
7
)) was found to be potent on 1L-6 induced STAT 3 activation because of the involvement of this activation in neuro-inflammation (
Moussaieff et al, 2007
, 
2008b
).

Boscartins I–K (
38–40
), Q (
46
), Z (
55
), A-H (
30–37
) and AO (
70, 70A
) were also tested against NO production using dexamethasone as positive control. Boscartins AO (
70, 70A
) showed potent inhibitory effects on NO production. However, boscartins I–K (
38–40
) did not show any considerable activity, and the other compounds exhibited weak anti-inflammatory activity (
Sun et al., 2019
; J. Yu et al., 2018).

The psychoactive activity of various cembranoids was realized by activating TRPV3 (Transient receptor potential vanilloid 3) channels in the brain of wild-type mice. TRPV3 mRNA is observed in neurons all over the brain (
Chung et al., 2004
; 
Moussaieff et al., 2008a
; 
Ramsey et al., 2006
). Incensole acetate (
7
) was found to be a potent TRPV3 against resulting in anti-depression like behavioural effects with associated changes in C-Fos activation in the brain. The compound induced calcium influence in TRPV3 channels. A significant decrease of corticosterone levels in mice also supported the anti-depression effect of incensole acetate.

Incensole (
6
) and incensone showed moderate potency to stimulate the TRPV3 mediated calcium inflow (

Moussaieff et al, 2008 
a

, 2012; 
Pollastro et al., 2016
). Several other synthetic analogues of incensole also showed moderate potency. Serratol (
14
) was identified as the most potent TRPV3 activator.

Incensole (
6
), incensole acetate (
7
), incensfuran (
21
) and incensone (
6A
) exhibited significant anti-depression effect in the forced swim test (EST) and tail suspension test (TST). These compounds induced elevated brain GABA levels, suggesting the involvement of a GABAergic mechanism. The molecular docking studies to elucidate the mode of action for the anxiolytic and anticonvulsant effects of the compounds were also performed (
Al-Harrasi et al., 2019b
).

The hepatoprotective activity of different cembranoids of 

Boswellia
species

were evaluated at 10 μM against paracetamol induced Hep G 
2
cell damage (
Sun et al., 2019
; 
Wang et al., 2020
; J. Wang et al., 2019). Bicyclol was used as the positive control. Incensole acetate (
7
) showed impressive hepatoprotective activity while incensole oxide (
8
), incensole oxide acetate (
9
), isoincensole oxide (
12
) and boscartin M (
42
) held only moderate activities. Boscartin A-H (
30–37
) was more potent than the positive control. Boscartins AC (
30–32
), AG (
62
), AN (
69
) and AP (
45
) also showed impressive activity.

Boscartins P (
45
) to Z (
55
) and AA to AG (
56–62
) were evaluated for hepatoprotective activity against D-galactosamine induced toxicity in HL-7702 cells using bicyclol as positive control. Most of the compounds were found to be active (
Sun et al., 2019
; 
Wang et al., 2020
; J. Wang et al., 2019).

The cytotoxicity of various cembranoids was examined (Ren et al., 2015; 
Schmidt et al., 2011
; 
Sun et al., 2019
). Serratol (
14
) showed cytotoxic activity against the L6 rat skeletal myoblast cell lines. Boscartins A-H (
30–37
) was evaluated against IEC-6 cells, but they did not show any activity. Boscartins P-AG (
45–62
) were also tested against several human cancer cell lines including Bel 7402 (human hematoma cell line) and A 2780 (human ovarian cancer cell line). However, these compounds did not show any obvious cytotoxicity against all these cell lines.

Boscartins AH (
63
) - AD (
59
), Q (
46
) and Z (
55
) were evaluated for antiproliferative activity against HCT-116 human colon cancer cell using cisplatin as positive control. All the compounds showed weak antiproliferative activity. However, boscartins I–K (
38–40
) -when tested against human breast cancer cell MCF-7 - did not show any considerable activity (Ren et al., 2015; 
Schmidt et al., 2011
; 
Sun et al., 2019
).

